            "answer_text": "Sometimes nothing at all, sometimes a lot, depending on which area of mathematics and which area of philosophy. Many think G\u00f6del's theorems in mathematics, which tell us about the limits of logic, tell us something important about the nature of the universe and have deep philosophical implications. Questions about existence and what it means to exist have branched two ways, one going off into mathematical logic and set theory and the other going off into non-mathematical philosophy. Whenever a branch of philosophy ends up being quantifiable, it ends up ceasing to be regarded as philosophy and regarded instead as physics or mathematics, so this reduces what would otherwise be a huge overlap. Mathematical logic and computation theory is particularly rich with philosophical implications. For example, there are questions over whether the operations of the brain can be reduced to a symbolic \"formal\" system or not, and whether concrete implementations of formal systems (computers) can be conscious (look up Searle's Chinese Room). The mathematician Roger Penrose regards G\u00f6del's theorems as proof that the human brain does something that a computer cannot replicate, but others disagree. Philosophy and mathematics intersect in physics, which was, after all, originally known as \"natural philosophy\". In the mathematical theory known as quantum mechanics, objects appear not to have definite states until observed, which conflicts with our ordinary intuition at the macroscopic scale. The paradox of Schr\u00f6dinger's Cat is as yet unresolved, but physicists have no problem using the mathematics while not worrying about the philosophical implications. Quantum mechanics has been described (I think by David Bohm) as seeming like the wrong answer to \"if a tree falls in a forest and no-one sees it fall, does it really fall?\". ",
