            "answer_text": "To say the least, philosophy generally encompasses topics concerning fundamental questions in life that have no definite answer. Words in philosophy are not well-defined (save the so-called \"mathematical philosophy\"), which encourages a culture of debate. Although both depends heavily on inference. Mathematics seeks not to explain world phenomena. Mathematical objects are well-defined but are approximation to nature at best. And it's only because of that that it makes sense to talk about proofs in mathematics. However, philosophy of mathematics could be characterized (arguably) as a blend of mathematics (mathematical logic) and philosophy (platonism, formalism, intuitionism). ",
